-- Malaysia's Ringgit Slips From 13-Year High; Bonds Steady Before Auction
-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 2010-09-23T08:13:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-23/malaysia-s-ringgit-slips-from-13-year-high-focus-on-bids-at-bond-auction.html
Malaysia’s ringgit fell the most in
a week, retreating from a 13-year high, as a technical gauge
that traders use to predict price swings signaled the dollar may
rebound.  The U.S. currency’s 14-day relative strength index was at
33 yesterday, approaching the 30 threshold that signals the
greenback is likely to strengthen. Southeast Asia’s third-
largest economy may experience a “slight”  moderation in
expansion in the second half due to a weaker global economy,
Prime Minister Najib Razak said Sept. 21. The government may
announce today the amount and date for its three-year bond
auction scheduled for this month. Bonds were little changed  “The appreciation pace has been a quite rapid and market
participants could turn cautious as key levels are broken,”
said  Akira Banno , a treasury adviser at Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi
UFJ Bhd. in Kuala Lumpur. “Investors would like to wait and see
the confidence level about the economic outlook.”  The ringgit dropped 0.2 percent to 3.0930 per dollar as of
4 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.
The currency reached 3.0872 today, the strongest level since
October 1997. Financial markets in Japan, China, Hong Kong and
South Korea are shut for a holiday.  The ringgit has appreciated 11 percent this year, the best
performance among Asia’s 10 most-active currencies. The currency
may reach 3.05 next month, Banno said.  Bond Auction  Malaysia’s benchmark three-year bonds were little changed,
keeping yields at a one-week high, as the government announced
plan to sell more debt next week.  The yield on the 3.21 percent note due May 2013 was
unchanged at 3.17 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The rate
has averaged 3.158 percent since June.  The government will sell 3 billion ringgit ($970 million)
of Shariah-compliant 2013 notes on Sept. 29, according to data
published by the central bank on its website today. The
government has sold 45.6 billion ringgit of bonds so far this
year, about a third less than in the same period in 2009.  Overseas investors owned a total 102 billion ringgit of
local-currency debt at the end of July, 47 percent more than at
the start of this year, central  bank data  show. They raised
their holdings of government bonds by 51 percent to a record 62
billion ringgit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
